<font color="#FF0000">COSTLY WAR FOR EVERYONE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Sep 14  0:31:59 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Vietnam left its scars on all Americans.  Most of all it scarred those who fought it willingly or unwillingly.  However, it also damaged those who left the country rather than serve in what most considered an immoral war.  It also scarred those of us who did neither, but who were consumed with rage, shame and guilt over what our country was doing and because many of our generation left fortunately placed than ourselves were being sucked into the nightmare.  All of our lives have been less than they could have been and many had no subsequent life at all.! <br><br>
The war also did immense damage to our political and economic life.  It ruptured the progressive coalition in the country that had moved the country (since the 30s) gradually toward a fairer economic system and evolving social order where there was real hope of social justice.  The war on poverty was the first victim in what became a wholesale conservative reaction. We and future generations of Americans suffer and will suffer greatly from that change in direction.<br><br>
Those of us who protested the war may share some responsibilty for that reaction.  However, one should realize that there were all kinds of gradations of protesters. Some of us confined ourselves to teach ins, talk shows, normal political activity, and an occassional peace march.  Others were much more militant and confrontational and sought to attack and tear down any institution lending any support to the war. Because many protestors were students, our universities received the most presure.  Some of us visited wounded soldiers in hospitals; others despised anyone who served in the immoral enterprise.  <br><br>
It wasn't easy for many of us to decide what the proper place on this spectrum was and we tended to drift in a more radical direction as the insanity went on and on and we were personally disillusioned by the assasination or and  frustration of the political leaders we had placed some hope in.  To the extend that this damaged progressive institutions without leaving anything in there place, the protests were regretable.  On the other hand, the breath and depth of the opposition did play a major role in convincing the government that it could not continue the war.<br><br>
With all the cost to the US in deaths, casualties, lost opportunities and subsequent political reaction, the costs to the people of both Vietnams was infinitely greater.  Our governments basic rationale for involvment in Vietnam was to contain Communism and Vietnam became a pawn in that endeavor as did many other third world countries.  Despite our failure in Vietnam, subsequent events have proved the foolishness of that rationale.  In spite of the mistakes, I'm proud that many Americans, unlike the Germans in WWII,  resisted this immoral war.       <br>
               <br>
 
